The effect of counterion on the topological structure
Compounds 1–6, constructed from the bib ligand and six kinds of manganese salts, illustrate a series of fascinating frameworks based on MnII nodes. In the progress of self-assembly, both the MnII ion and bib ligand keep its own coordination pattern, the octahedron and bidentate linker, respectively. Significantly, in all of six compounds, four equatorial sites of MnII ion are exclusively occupied by the bib ligand, and each bib ligand bridges two MnII ions. In such a way, the octahedral coordinated MnII ion of 1–6 is primarily connected by the bib ligand into a 2D (4,4) layer, which can be viewed as a common feature to build up six compounds by different linkers, such as the bib ligand and inorganic anions, and also will keep the consistency and continuity of structural variation. All above similarities greatly facilitates us to perform a systematic study on the effect of counterion on the topological structure. Six kinds of counterions in 1–6 play various roles due to different coordination affinities and molecular sizes, and finally lead to diverse frameworks under the cooperation of bib ligand (
).
